{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>NadR functions as a transcriptional regulator in Salmonella enterica [[cite:PUB00008725]]. When NAD+ is available, NadR is bound with its corepressor, NAD+, and this leads to DNA binding activity that acts as a repressor for several genes needed for de novo NAD+ biosynthesis [[cite:PUB00092573], [cite:PUB00092574]]. NadR also possesses both NMN adenylyltransferase (NMNAT) and nicotinamide ribonucleoside kinase (RNK) activity  [[cite:PUB00091762]]. Haemophilus influenzae lacks de novo biosynthetic pathways for NAD+ and also lacks a helix-turn-helix DNA binding domain present in NadR of S. enterica. H. influenzae NadR  does not function as a repressor, but has enzymatic activity. Nicotinamide riboside (NR) enters the NAD+ resynthesis pathway after uptake, it is phosphorylated to obtain NMN by a nicotinamide RNK activity, and subsequently, NAD+ is synthesized from NMN and ATP via an NMNAT activity [[cite:PUB00092575]]. NadR is a multifunctional biosynthesis/regulator protein.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pirsf" {"PIRSF004776" "Bifunctional transcription regulator NadR (NMN adenylytransferase/ribosylnicotinamide kinase)"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "NAD biosynthesis/regulator protein NadR", "short" "NAD_NadR"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 5, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 276, "taxa" 2211, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 2065, "sets" 0, "proteins" 2064, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1484}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"ec" {"displayName" "ENZYME", "description" "ENZYME is a repository of information relative to the nomenclature of enzymes. It is primarily based on the recommendations of the Nomenclature Committee of the International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (IUBMB) and it describes 